---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "HIGH Dividend Analysis & History",
    "description": "Evaluate the HIGH ETF dividend yield, options-based income approach, and track historical distribution data.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best high dividend stocks?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The best high dividend stocks often balance strong current yield with sustainable payout ratios. We frequently analyze covered call funds like the HIGH ETF, which generates significant income through options premiums."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I find high yield dividend stocks?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Finding high yield dividend stocks requires looking beyond just the headline percentage. Evaluating the source of the yield—whether it's traditional earnings, REIT structures, or options strategies—is critical."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are high dividend yield stocks safe?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Not always. Extremely high dividend yield stocks can sometimes signal underlying distress. However, structured products like the HIGH ETF manage this risk by using index options rather than individual distressed equities."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which are the top high dividend stocks 2025?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For the top high dividend stocks 2025, many investors are pivoting toward derivative-income ETFs like HIGH or JEPI, which capitalize on market volatility to maintain high payouts."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Where can I find high dividend yield stocks 2025?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Our platform continuously updates the list of high dividend yield stocks 2025, tracking exact monthly payout histories and fluctuating yields based on current market data."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What defines high yield dividend stocks 2025?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "In the current macro environment, high yield dividend stocks 2025 generally refers to those consistently paying over 5-7% annually, often achieved through specialized strategies rather than traditional corporate dividends."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the outlook for high yield dividend stocks 2026?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The outlook for high yield dividend stocks 2026 will heavily rely on interest rate policy. If risk-free rates fall, the demand and valuation for high-yielding equities and income ETFs will likely increase."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do high dividend growth stocks compare?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "High dividend growth stocks typically offer a lower starting yield but increase their payouts annually. They are designed for long-term total return, unlike immediate high-income vehicles like the HIGH ETF."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="HIGH Dividend Analysis & History"
  description="Is the HIGH ETF the ultimate income generator? We analyze its 8% yield, distribution history, and payout strategy."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/high-dividend-stocks"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>HIGH Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Complete yield metrics, historical distribution data, and passive income calculator</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>HIGH Dividend Profile</h2>
      <p>The Simplify Volatility Premium ETF (HIGH) is a specialized income vehicle designed to generate substantial yields by systematically selling short-term equity index options. It appeals to investors seeking massive current income who are comfortable with derivative-based strategies.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Current Yield & Metrics</h3>
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th>Current Trailing Yield</th>
              <td>8.03%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Payout Frequency</th>
              <td>Monthly</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Underlying Strategy</th>
              <td>Volatility Premium / Short Vol</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Expense Ratio</th>
              <td>0.50%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>Because HIGH generates income by shorting implied volatility, its performance and dividend payouts are highly sensitive to market turbulence. It functions very differently from traditional <a href="/qqqi-dividend-history">QQQI Dividend History</a> strategies or standard index funds like <a href="/voo-dividend">VOO</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Monthly Dividend History</h2>
      <p>Review the historical monthly distributions for the HIGH ETF. Because the strategy monetizes volatility premiums, the payout amounts vary month-to-month based on market conditions.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Ex-Dividend Date</th>
            <th>Amount ($)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>2026-02-24</td><td>$0.1100</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2026-01-27</td><td>$0.1200</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-12-23</td><td>$0.1300</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-11-21</td><td>$0.1500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-10-28</td><td>$0.1500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-09-25</td><td>$0.1500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-08-26</td><td>$0.1600</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-07-28</td><td>$0.1600</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-06-25</td><td>$0.1600</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-05-27</td><td>$0.2000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-04-25</td><td>$0.1500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-03-26</td><td>$0.1000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-02-25</td><td>$0.1000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2025-01-28</td><td>$0.1100</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-12-23</td><td>$0.1100</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-11-25</td><td>$0.1400</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-10-28</td><td>$0.1400</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-09-25</td><td>$0.1400</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-08-27</td><td>$0.1500</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-07-26</td><td>$0.2000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-06-25</td><td>$0.2000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-05-24</td><td>$0.1400</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-04-25</td><td>$0.1400</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-03-25</td><td>$0.1600</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2024-02-26</td><td>$0.2000</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Passive Income Calculator</h2>
      <p>Estimate the substantial cash flow generated by this volatility premium strategy. Input your exact holdings below.</p>

      <div class="card" id="calc-container">
        <label style="display:block; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:0.5rem; color:var(--text-secondary);">Number of Shares Owned</label>
        <input type="number" id="sharesInput" placeholder="e.g. 500" style="width:100%; padding:0.75rem; border-radius:8px; border:1px solid var(--border-color); background:var(--bg-color); color:var(--text-primary); font-size:1rem; margin-bottom:1rem;" />

        <label style="display:block; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:0.5rem; color:var(--text-secondary);">Average Price per Share ($)</label>
        <input type="number" id="priceInput" placeholder="e.g. 23.50" style="width:100%; padding:0.75rem; border-radius:8px; border:1px solid var(--border-color); background:var(--bg-color); color:var(--text-primary); font-size:1rem; margin-bottom:1.5rem;" />

        <button id="calculateBtn" style="background:var(--accent-color); color:#fff; padding:0.75rem 1.5rem; border:none; border-radius:8px; font-weight:600; cursor:pointer; width:100%; font-size:1rem;">Calculate Income</button>

        <div id="results" style="display:none; margin-top:1.5rem; padding-top:1.5rem; border-top:1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">
            <span style="color:var(--text-secondary);">Estimated Annual Income:</span>
            <span id="annualIncome" style="font-weight:700; color:var(--accent-color);">$0.00</span>
          </div>
          <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between;">
            <span style="color:var(--text-secondary);">Estimated Monthly Payout:</span>
            <span id="monthlyIncome" style="font-weight:700;">$0.00</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the best high dividend stocks?</summary>
        <p>The best high dividend stocks often balance strong current yield with sustainable payout ratios. We frequently analyze covered call funds like the HIGH ETF, which generates significant income through options premiums.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I find high yield dividend stocks?</summary>
        <p>Finding high yield dividend stocks requires looking beyond just the headline percentage. Evaluating the source of the yield—whether it's traditional earnings, REIT structures, or options strategies—is critical.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are high dividend yield stocks safe?</summary>
        <p>Not always. Extremely high dividend yield stocks can sometimes signal underlying distress. However, structured products like the HIGH ETF manage this risk by using index options rather than individual distressed equities.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which are the top high dividend stocks 2025?</summary>
        <p>For the top high dividend stocks 2025, many investors are pivoting toward derivative-income ETFs like HIGH or JEPI, which capitalize on market volatility to maintain high payouts.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Where can I find high dividend yield stocks 2025?</summary>
        <p>Our platform continuously updates the list of high dividend yield stocks 2025, tracking exact monthly payout histories and fluctuating yields based on current market data.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What defines high yield dividend stocks 2025?</summary>
        <p>In the current macro environment, high yield dividend stocks 2025 generally refers to those consistently paying over 5-7% annually, often achieved through specialized strategies rather than traditional corporate dividends.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the outlook for high yield dividend stocks 2026?</summary>
        <p>The outlook for high yield dividend stocks 2026 will heavily rely on interest rate policy. If risk-free rates fall, the demand and valuation for high-yielding equities and income ETFs will likely increase.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do high dividend growth stocks compare?</summary>
        <p>High dividend growth stocks typically offer a lower starting yield but increase their payouts annually. They are designed for long-term total return, unlike immediate high-income vehicles like the HIGH ETF.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const btn = document.getElementById('calculateBtn');
      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('sharesInput');
      const priceInput = document.getElementById('priceInput');
      const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('results');
      const annualSpan = document.getElementById('annualIncome');
      const monthlySpan = document.getElementById('monthlyIncome');

      const YIELD = 0.0803; // 8.03%

      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const price = parseFloat(priceInput.value) || 0;

        const totalValue = shares * price;
        const annual = totalValue * YIELD;
        const monthly = annual / 12;

        annualSpan.textContent = '$' + annual.toLocaleString(undefined, {minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2});
        monthlySpan.textContent = '$' + monthly.toLocaleString(undefined, {minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2});

        resultsDiv.style.display = 'block';
      });
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
